<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-213-400  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 213 400.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  Feb 16 1989 n1151 p65(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Publish and be scanned. (computer scanners)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Green-Armytage, Jonathan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Scanners derive their technology and standards mainly from thefacsimile (fax) machine.andP;  They have found a natural niche in thedesktop publishing market as a means of entering either text orimage into a computer file.andP;  Adding scanning capabilities to asystem requires a set of components, including the scanner itself,an extra circuit board, a cable and some software.andP;  The scannersthemselves employ either a photographic lens or a strip oflight-sensitive diodes forming a charge-coupled device (CCD) tolook at the image.andP;  CCD units are most common as fax machines useCCD technology.andP;  Some have flat glass panels to handle books andother awkward items.andP;  Some only handle single sheets of paper.andP;  Afew scanning devices are hand-held.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ScanningOptical Character ReadersTechnologyEquipment Acquisition.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>